prompt:
The motion-staging layer of our stepper-driver console runs on a thread where allocation is banned outright, and we currently fake a bounded list with a raw array plus a count field in three different places. I want that replaced by one proper container: InlineVec<T, N>, a fixed-capacity vector whose elements live inside the object itself. One new file, inlinevec.hpp, header-only, C++20, stdlib only.

Surface:

    template <class T, std::size_t N>
    class InlineVec {
    public:
        InlineVec() noexcept;                 // empty; constructs no T whatsoever
        ~InlineVec();                          // destroys the live elements
        InlineVec(const InlineVec&);
        InlineVec& operator=(const InlineVec&);
        InlineVec(InlineVec&&);                // see noexcept note below
        InlineVec& operator=(InlineVec&&);
        bool push_back(const T& v);
        bool push_back(T&& v);
        template <class... Args> bool emplace_back(Args&&... args);
        void pop_back();                       // callers guarantee non-empty
        void clear() noexcept;
        T& operator[](std::size_t i);
        const T& operator[](std::size_t i) const;
        T* data() noexcept;  const T* data() const noexcept;
        T* begin();  T* end();  const T* begin() const;  const T* end() const;
        std::size_t size() const noexcept;
        bool empty() const noexcept;
        static constexpr std::size_t capacity() noexcept;   // == N
    };

The rules, learned the hard way from the raw-array versions:

- Storage is inline: every element sits inside the InlineVec object's own footprint, correctly aligned for T. No heap, ever. Elements are contiguous, data() points at element 0.
- An empty container constructs no T. Our command types have no default constructor, so `T buf[N]` is not an option — construct elements in place when they are pushed, destroy them individually when popped/cleared/overwritten. pop_back and clear destroy immediately, not at some later point.
- push_back/emplace_back return true on success. When the container is already full they return false and construct NOTHING (check capacity before creating the element, not after). No exceptions for the full case.
- Exception safety, because command constructors can throw: if the element constructor throws inside push_back/emplace_back, the container is exactly as it was (strong guarantee). If an element copy throws mid copy-construction, the partially built copy is destroyed before the exception escapes — no leaked live objects. Copy assignment is all-or-nothing: if any element copy throws, the target keeps its old contents untouched. Self-assignment is harmless.
- Moves transfer element-wise (there is no heap buffer to steal): the target ends up with the source's elements, the source ends up empty(). Move construction must be noexcept whenever T's move constructor is noexcept — we put these inside std::vector and want moves, not copies, on reallocation.
- Assume only that T is copy-constructible, move-constructible and destructible. Never assign to a T; never require T() to exist.
- Exact live-object accounting: every element constructed is destroyed exactly once, including on every early-exit path above. The tests count constructions and destructions of an instrumented type and will notice any drift.
- N is at least 1; size() never exceeds capacity(); pop_back on empty and operator[] out of range are the caller's problem (no checks required).

`make test` is the acceptance gate; Makefile, mintest.h and test_inlinevec.cpp are fixed.
